## (1) The time "teleport" on resume (the snap/jump)

### Root cause

Line 112:
```ts
program.uniforms.uTime.value = t * 0.001;
```
The `t` passed into a `requestAnimationFrame` callback is a `DOMHighResTimeStamp` measured from the same time origin as `performance.now()` (MDN: "similar to calling `performance.now()` at the start of the callback"). It is **absolute wall-clock time**, not elapsed animation time.

When your `IntersectionObserver` or `visibilitychange` handler calls `pause()` (lines 120-125), `cancelAnimationFrame` stops the loop, but the clock `t` keeps running in the real world. When `play()` fires again, the very next frame sets `uTime` to a value that is larger by the **entire paused duration** (could be many seconds or minutes for a backgrounded tab). The fbm domain warp at lines 32-34 advances proportionally, so the smoke snaps to a completely different state in a single frame. That is your jump.

This is the classic rAF pause bug: MDN explicitly notes rAF "calls are paused in most browsers when running in background tabs," so on `visibilitychange` you must reset your time reference on resume, never integrate the gap.

### Fix: accumulate your own delta-time clock

Maintain a private `elapsed` accumulator and a `lastFrame` marker. On every frame, add the clamped delta. On resume, reset `lastFrame` so the gap is discarded.

```ts
let elapsed = 0;        // animation time, only advances while visible
let lastFrame = 0;      // timestamp of previous rendered frame
let running = false;
let raf = 0;

const loop = (t: number) => {
  // First frame after (re)start: seed lastFrame, contribute zero dt.
  if (lastFrame === 0) lastFrame = t;

  // Clamp dt so a missed/slow frame or a resume slip cannot cause a jump.
  // 0.05s = ~3 frames at 60Hz is a safe ceiling for a decorative bg.
  const dt = Math.min(0.05, (t - lastFrame) * 0.001);
  lastFrame = t;
  elapsed += dt;

  program.uniforms.uTime.value = elapsed;   // <- monotonic, gap-free

  // ...velocity + render here (see section 2)...
  raf = requestAnimationFrame(loop);
};

const play = () => {
  if (running) return;
  running = true;
  lastFrame = 0;            // <- force re-seed; discards the paused interval
  raf = requestAnimationFrame(loop);
};
const pause = () => {
  if (!running) return;
  running = false;
  cancelAnimationFrame(raf);
};
```

The two load-bearing lines are `lastFrame = 0` in `play()` (drops the gap) and `Math.min(0.05, ...)` (caps any residual slip). MDN's own delta-time guidance is to derive progress from the timestamp argument rather than assume a fixed step, which also makes the animation speed consistent across 60Hz/120Hz displays.

Note: because `elapsed` is now bounded by visible time only, it grows far more slowly than absolute `performance.now()`, which also helps section (4)'s precision issue.

